{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9919908e-ac82-42b7-b5f1-680ea18d45b2","content":"The tutorial you found is **outdated**. Here's what changed:\n\n### `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` — No longer needed\n\nStarting in **.NET 9**, MAUI applies safe area insets **by default** on iOS. You no longer need this platform-specific property. Just remove it — your content will automatically avoid the notch/Dynamic Island.\n\n### `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` — Still correct ✅\n\nThis is the right approach for letting a background image bleed into the unsafe area (behind the notch, status bar, home indicator). For example:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\">\n    <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n        <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        <!-- Other content here will still respect safe area \n             if placed in a nested layout without IgnoreSafeArea -->\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n### Summary for .NET 10\n\n| Property | Status | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` | **Unnecessary** | Safe area is on by default since .NET 9 |\n| `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` (on views) | **Correct** | Use to extend into unsafe areas (backgrounds, etc.) |\n| `Page.IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` | Available | Opts the entire page out of safe area handling |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e9749f58-6c5d-46df-af32-75669aa6f24c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - for handling the iPhone notch\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for a background image\n\nLet me think about what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling has evolved. Let me recall:\n\n- In earlier versions of .NET MAUI (and Xamarin.Forms), there was `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` which was a platform-specific API.\n\n\n- In .NET 9+, they introduced cross-platform safe area support with `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` as a property on layouts and pages, which deprecated the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` approach.\n- The key breaking change in .NET 9 was that safe area padding is now applied by default on iOS, so `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` is no longer needed.\n- For .NET 10, the pattern is to use `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on layouts or views when you want content to extend beyond the safe area, rather than trying to enable safe area handling.\n- Any tutorial recommending the old `UseSafeArea` approach is likely outdated.\n- For .NET 10, the safe area is handled automatically on iOS, so I just need to confirm that using `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the Grid for the background image is the right modern approach.","outputTokens":1196,"requestId":"F3C9:2D9D7A:1ED722:24B873:69E81D9E"},"id":"396e1460-5f41-431d-b362-abee7baef9bc","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:00:36.718Z","parentId":"5183d41a-0a71-480d-b84b-ec048094fcd3"}
